:D000728"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "androgen", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9973419308662415, "span": {"begin": 619, "end": 627}}, {"id": ["mesh:D013196"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "dihydrotestosterone", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.7413566708564758, "span": {"begin": 628, "end": 647}}, {"id": ["mesh:D013196"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "DHT", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9986149072647095, "span": {"begin": 649, "end": 652}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:367", "231", "2232"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "AR", "obj": "gene", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 669, "end": 671}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:10116"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "rats", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.9571639895439148, "span": {"begin": 902, "end": 906}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:9606"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "humans", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.9799143671989441, "span": {"begin": 954, "end": 960}}, {"id": ["mesh:D013739"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "testosterone", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.991063117980957, "span": {"begin": 979, "end": 991}}, {"id": ["mesh:D005832"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "genital malformations", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9999967217445374, "span": {"begin": 1097, "end": 1118}}, {"id": ["mesh:D007021"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "hypospadias", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.999985933303833, "span": {"begin": 1148, "end": 1159}}, {"id": ["mesh:D013739"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "testosterone", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9912994503974915, "span": {"begin": 1253, "end": 1265}}, {"id": ["mesh:D007021"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "hypospadias", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.999992847442627, "span": {"begin": 1295, "end": 1306}}], "text": "This non-adjacent KER describes a fetal decrease in testis testosterone leading to hypospadias in male offspring. In this KER, intratesticular testosterone levels can both be measured in whole testes homogenates or by measuring ex vivo testosterone production from cultured testes.  In male mammals, the testes differentiate in early fetal life and begin steroidogenesis to synthesize testosterone. Testosterone is secreted from the fetal testes for initiation of differentiation of the male reproductive tissues. Testosterone acts at the androgen receptor (AR) or is converted by 5&alpha;-reductase to the more potent androgen dihydrotestosterone (DHT). Activation of AR in the bipotential genital tubercle starts differentiation into a penis. While penis differentiation is a longer process, programming of the genital tubercle is largely constrained to a fixed period (gestational day (GD) 16-20 in rats, presumably gestational week (GW)&nbsp;8-14 in humans), when testicular testosterone production is high (Sharpe, 2020; Welsh et al., 2014). Failure of proper penis differentiation can cause genital malformations, of which the most common is hypospadias, where the urethral opening is on the underside of the penis.  A decrease in intratesticular testosterone levels may therefore lead to hypospadias in male offspring.", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 16:17:50 +0000 2026"}